{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6156a4fd-f743-4345-948a-ea32c05aab01","content":"No repo-specific docs cover this topic. Here's the general guidance:\n\nOn macOS, NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR tool). To get a crash dump:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** – run `ulimit -c unlimited` in your shell before launching the app.\n\n2. **Check macOS core dump location** – by default, macOS writes cores to `/cores/core.<pid>`. Verify with:\n   ```\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **If `/cores/` is missing or empty**, create it and set permissions:\n   ```\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Disable SIP restrictions (if needed)** – on modern macOS, System Integrity Protection can prevent core dumps for signed binaries. You may need to remove the code signature:\n   ```\n   codesign --remove-signature ./your-app\n   ```\n\n5. **Reproduce the crash** – run the app again. A `core.<pid>` file should appear in `/cores/`.\n\n6. **Analyze with lldb**:\n   ```\n   lldb ./your-app -c /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   Use `bt` for a backtrace, `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n7. **Alternative – use lldb directly** – attach lldb at startup to catch the crash live:\n   ```\n   lldb ./your-app\n   run\n   ```\n   When it crashes, you're already in the debugger.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"33fae3b7-2782-4fad-99aa-6aa408951df0","outputTokens":367,"requestId":"2C44:97105:13EF855:16B8F67:69F94D73"},"id":"6f615d26-8a64-4f98-be58-cf0a2d6a2d31","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:53:03.734Z","parentId":"2994a192-d40a-4803-a481-a0655a3e8966"}
